    <div class="label">Why Marching</div>
    <h2>Your Feet Are the<br><span class="accent-text">Honest Measurement.</span></h2>
    <p class="lead">You don't need someone else to tell you when your system got overloaded. Your feet will tell you. Automatically. In real time.</p>

    <div class="march-why" id="marchWhy">
      <div class="mw-row">
        <div class="mw-icon">🦶</div>
        <div>
          <h4>The feet don't lie</h4>
          <p>When the speaking gets hard — when you lose the structure, rush the explain, or can't find the ending — your feet slow down. <strong>Without you deciding to slow them.</strong> That is your nervous system telling you exactly where your capacity currently ends.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="mw-row">
        <div class="mw-icon">🔁</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Simulates divided attention</h4>
          <p>Real pressure never comes alone. You are always managing the room, reading the faces, tracking the time, and speaking — all at once. <strong>Marching replicates that split.</strong> Your brain learns to hold structure when something else is pulling at it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="mw-row">
        <div class="mw-icon">📈</div>
        <div>
          <h4>Builds capacity, not just awareness</h4>
          <p>The other five days have been about seeing and naming. Today is about expanding. <strong>Every rep where you hold the rhythm and finish the ending is a rep where your nervous system learns that it can.</strong></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="mw-row">
        <div class="mw-icon">🎯</div>
        <div>
          <h4>The goal is not to sound perfect</h4>
